## Strongest abstractions
1. `Agentic OS` has the cleanest receipt contract. A run is not “one blob of state”; it is a bundle of `inputs`, `outputs`, `policy`, `benchmark`, `gate`, plus a hash manifest in `/Users/jobs/Desktop/agentic-os/receipts/runs/...`. This was built to prevent untraceable promotion, evidence-free claims, and context drift. Its separation is unusually crisp: runtime execution in `run_task`, evaluator logic in `evaluate_benchmark`, policy checks in `evaluate_policy`, and promotion in `gate_decision`, all inside `/Users/jobs/Desktop/agentic-os/scripts/run_core_loop.py`.

2. `macro-hard` has the strongest policy-selection loop. It treats heuristics and repair settings as candidate policies, not truths. The loop mines hard failures, adapts suite weights to the current loss surface, computes a single macro score, then only promotes a challenger if it improves enough without regressing critical suites or QPM. This was built to prevent heuristic accretion, aggregate-score self-deception, and “faster but worse” promotion. Runtime is external to the selector; evaluator is `network_effects`; policy is `policy_autoselect`.

3. `dreaming-kernel` has the strongest runtime/evaluator separation. The Rust binary explicitly refuses cognitive task logic and only routes signals, executes ops, and writes receipts. All task cognition and evaluation live in `manifest.yaml` and Python workers like `/Users/jobs/Desktop/dreaming-kernel/scripts/quality_gate.py` and `/Users/jobs/Desktop/dreaming-kernel/scripts/benchmark_ab.py`. This was built to prevent the runtime from silently improvising policy, and to stop hidden task-specific heuristics from creeping into the kernel.

4. The best gate-linked benchmark slice pattern comes from `macro-hard` plus `dreaming-kernel`. `macro-hard` uses named critical suites and suite floors from `/Users/jobs/Desktop/macro-hard/config/requirements.meta_minimax.json`; `dreaming-kernel` uses route accuracy, artifact minima, and external proof in `/Users/jobs/Desktop/dreaming-kernel/docs/QUALITY_GATE.json`. These were built to prevent a good aggregate score from masking regressions in the exact slices that matter.

5. The best anti-heuristic framework is `macro-hard`’s default-off heuristic policy. `/Users/jobs/Desktop/macro-hard/README.md` and `/Users/jobs/Desktop/macro-hard/config/requirements.meta_minimax.json` keep `heuristics.mode=off` and `repair_retries=0` as safe defaults, then allow `seed` or `distill` only as challengers that must win A/B. `/Users/jobs/Desktop/macro-hard/scripts/heuristic_distiller.py` only turns failures into active heuristics after those failures are mined and counted. This was built to empirically keep heuristics that reduce loss and kill heuristics that merely feel helpful.

6. `dreaming-kernel` adds one more valuable abstraction: non-circular proof slices. Its quality gate requires external proof, and its benchmark reports show the system failing closed when route eval or external proof is weak. That is a direct guard against self-grading loops and “internal benchmark says we’re great” inflation.

